english:
  title: Four Compositions on Retreat at Turtle Grandson's Place
  author: Kang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I.
    A bowl of ice-water cold as jade,
    the window draws in rain's mist, dampening my robe and crown.
    Children come running with news—the southern stream overflows!
    We strike and catch the silver fish, suddenly the plate runs full.

    II.
    Lotus shadows flicker across the pond, dimpling the clear water,
    the jade-green bird forsakes its prey, crossing slowly through the stream.
    Too lazy to attend court ceremony, I seek instead the wild's delight—
    the southern city's wind and moon, they belong now only to me.

    III.
    Carriages and horses no longer pass before my gate,
    green moss gathers rain into embroidered patterns of decay.
    Night deepens in my modest cottage—no dreams come at all,
    only the lamp's small flame, falling, rising, falling once again.

    IV.
    Clouds hang heavy, obscuring all within an arm's span,
    after the rain, clear waters flood the empty courtyard stones.
    I burn incense in small script—wisps of smoke drift upward,
    watching idly as the swallows peck the mud before my gate.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Turtle Grandson''s Place (龜孫): This appears to be the name of a retreat or residence where the poet composed these four poems.'
  - key: ''
    value: The four poems form a cohesive suite depicting rural retirement, moving from scenes of simple living and fishing, through withdrawal from court life, to the poet's final contentment in solitude and observation of nature.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Small script (小篆): An ancient Chinese script style, here used poetically to suggest refined, deliberate actions—burning incense with intention.'
